2.7. Effective development based on artificial gas
reservoir by horizontal well fracturing
Artificial gas reservoir is to achieve effective development
of natural gas from shale formation on a large scale by manual
intervention including taking black gas-bearing shale formation
as sweet spot area unit, in which the well groups are deployed
in a scientific and rational way and shale formation is subjected
to transformation by massive hydraulic fracturing to form dense
fracture network and build artificial highly permeable area and
rebuild seepage field to greatly change subsurface fluid
seepage environment and supplement formation energy. Years
of exploration shows that multi-stage fracturing technique for
horizontal well is able to make artificial permeability in shale
reservoir, being an effective technique to establish artificial
shale gas reservoir. PurpleHayes Well 1H in Utica Shale Gas
Field is taken as an example; horizontal section is 5652 m in
length and subjected to fracturing in 124 stages, with fracturing
fluid of 11.3  104 m3 injected to achieve that single well is
14.1  104 m3/d in gas output and 159.6 t/d [24] in oil output.
Free gas is prior product in production process of gas well,
therefore, single well is higher in initial output; with the
decrease of formation pressure, adsorbed gas is subjected to
desorption in organic substance and flows into highly perme-
able fracture network channel, but the highly permeable frac-
ture network channel shows shortage of gas supply, therefore,
its later output is on the low side in long-period gas production.
Horizontal well in Haynesville Shale Gas is taken as an
example, the single well is 28  104 m3/d in initial output, with
output for the first year up to 30% of recoverable reserves and
output for the first three years up to 50% [25,26] of recoverable
reserves. On the premise of taking no account of economical
efficiency in gas well development, production period shall be
up to more than 30 years [13,26].
3. Present situation of shale gas in the US
The US starts shale gas revolution and achieves constant
innovation and development in terms of theoretic knowledge,
key technical equipment and management mode of shale gas to
drive global development in shale gas industry. Data from EIA
(2017) show that the shale gas output in the US in 2016 was
4447  108 m3, having grown by 200  108 m3, namely 4.6%.
3.1. Development process of shale gas in the US
There are 3 stages in development of shale gas in the US by
and large: Scientific exploration stage, technical breakthrough
stage and mature development stage.
3.1.1. Scientific exploration stage (1821e1996)
William A. Hart drilled the first oil gas well onshore in Fre-
donia of New York in the US in 1821, having succeeded in
development of shale gas for the first time. The well is 21 m in
depth and the reservoir is Dunkirk shale in Devonian system with
buried depth of 8.2 m and production period up to 37 years [27].
Some enterprises began to take shale gas as unconventional oil
and gas resource for exploration in a down-to-earth way and
started pilot development of shale gas fields in Antrim, Barnett
and Devonian in succession [28]. 8 production wells were drilled
in Antrim Shale in Michigan Basin in 1940 for shale gas devel-
opment on a small scale [29] in 1940. Ohio Shale and Cleveland
Shale were subjected to small scale fracturing trial to increase
production in 1965, having obtained favorable effect [28].
Under the influence of oil crisis in 1970s, the US govern-
ment issued several policies to promote development of un-
conventional oil and gas such as shale gas, including Eastern
Gas Shales Project started in 1976 with focus on trial devel-
opment [28] of shale gas in Devonian System in Michigan,
Illinois and Appalachian basins; Windfall Profit Act issued in
1977 (Department of Energy Organization Act) to boost
development of unconventional oil and gas [28]. The US
experienced remarkable growth from 18.4  108 m3 in 1978 to
56.6  108 m3 in 1992 in shale gas output in the period.
During this period, the shale gas output took shape and
acquired some key geologic knowledge and carried out a
number of explorative developments as a result of favorable
policy of the US government. The shale gas output was up to
80  108 m3 in shale gas fields in Antrim and Marcellus in
1977 [28] to make certain three types of geneses including
biological genesis, thermal genesis and mixed genesis [29] and
put forward concept [13] of continuous oil and gas accu-
mulation with trial made to increase production by small
scale fracturing, gel fracturing and horizontal well [28,30].
3.1.2. Technical breakthrough stage (1997e2003)
A breakthrough has been made in key engineering technology
for shale gas, the application of technologies for multi-stage
fracturing for horizontal well, large-scale hydraulic fracturing
and multi-well pad based exploitation has made shale gas
resource subject to effective development. Mitchell Energy &
Development Corporation headed by Mitchell has drilled more
