3.2. Case analysis of typical shale gas field
3.2.1. First shale gas field to make a breakthroughdBarnett
Shale Gas Field
Barnett Shale Gas Field is located in Fort Worth Basin in
mid-north of Texas (Fig. 2), the principal target stratum is
Barnett Shale in Mississippian System, with burial depth from
1980m to 2591 m, thickness from 30 m to 180 m, TOC from
4% to 5%, Ro value from 0.8% to 1.4%, total porosity from 4%
to 5%, technical recoverable reserves up to 7362  108 m3 [9].
The gas field covers an area of 15500 km2, in which the core
area is 5000 km2, shale thickness is from 100 m to 230 m; the
peripheral area is 10500 km2, the shale thickness is more than
30 m [9]. The typical well is from 2000m to 3000 m in vertical
depth, with horizontal section length from 1000 m to 1500 m
and construction process of large amount of fluid and
displacement and low sand-liquid ratio adopted to carry out
volume fracturing in 10 stages, the single well cost is USD 2
million, with initial output up to 5.3  104 m3/d and ultimate
recoverable reserves up to 7000  104 m3.
In 1981, Mitchell Energy & Development Corporation took
the lead in drilling the first batch of evaluation wells, the first 33
wells fails to be up to economic output, with high energy gas
fracturing, foam fracturing and gel fracturing adopted for reser-
voir transformation in succession and poor effects. In 1997, since
large scale slick water fracturing technology greatly reduced
development cost and improved single well output, making it
possible to carry out commercial development of straight well.
Since 2003, with the application of horizontal well technology
and straight well re-fracturing technology, the single well output
has been further increased. In 2004, maturity and rapid gener-
alization of multi-stage fracturing technology for horizontal well
made shale gas output in peripheral area reach 466  108 m3. In
2008, Operation mode of multi-well pad was subjected to
extensive application, which further reduced development cost
and increased gas field output at a great pace, with output up to
466  108 m3 in 2011, making it become second largest shale gas
field in the US. Its output was 330  108 m3 in 2016, being the
fifth largest shale gas field in the US.
