4.2.3. Shale gas in Ordos Basin
Ordos Basin is an important production area for natural gas
in China, being in five provinces including Shaanxi, Gansu,
Ningxia, Inner Mogolia and Shanxi, covering an area of about
20  104 km2, with 4 series of organic rich shales developed
from top to bottom, namely shale in Liangping Formation in
Ordovician System in marine facies in Lower Paleozoic, shale
in Shanxi Formation, Taiyuan Formation, Benxi Formation in
Carboniferous-Permian in transition facies in Upper Paleozoic
and shale in Yanchang Formation in Triassic System in conti-
nental facies in Mesozoic. Shale in Carboniferous System and
Permian System in transition facies in Upper Paleozoic has been
proven to be the main source rock in conventional gas fields in
Jingbian, Sulige, Wushenqi, Yulin and Daniudi. Organic rich
shale in Ordos Basin is from 700 m to 4000 m in burial depth,
from 20 m to 200 m in thickness, 2.6494  104 km2 in favorable
area, from 1.5% to 11.37% (average: 6.95%) in TOC, from 0.5%
to 2.98% (average: 1.29%) in Ro value, from 35.04% to 56.95%
(average: 46.0%) in quartz mineral content, from 1.8% to 7.4%
(average:3.12%) in total porosity, from 1.38 to 4.36 m3/t
(average: 2.45 m3/t) in gas content, from 0.98 to 1.20 in for-
mation pressure coefficient, 7.1537  1012 m3 in geologic re-
sources, 0.9759  1012 m3 in recoverable reserves.
In 2011, Yanchang Petroleum Group drilled Liuping 177
well in southeast of Ordos Basin, with shale in Yanchang
Formation of Triassic subjected to fracturing test to achieve
daily output of shale gas up to 2350 m3, and then it drilled
Liuping 171, Xin 57, Xin 59 and Yanye 1 wells in succession,
with shale in Yanchang Formation of Triassic System sub-
jected to fracturing test to achieve daily output of shale gas up
to 1779e2413 m3. In 2012, Yanchang Yan'an National Shale
Gas Demonstration Zone of was established in Zhiluo-
Xiasiwan in the area of mining right of Yanchang Petro-
leum. In 2017, shale in Carboniferous System and Permian
System in Ji 2e4, Daji 27, Daji 41 wells on east end of Ordos
Basin drilled by Coal Seam Gas Company affiliated to Pet-
roChina were subjected to fracturing, with daily output of
shale gas from 2885  104 m3 to 8254  104 m3, and now,
shale in Carboniferous System and Permian System in almost
10 wells was subjected to gas testing; China Geological Sur-
vey drilled Well Zhong 4 in the west of the Basin, with
Wulalik Formation in Upper Ordovician System as target
stratum and daily output in test on well section from 4050 m to
4056 m up to 4.12  104 m3. According to practice in
exploration and development of shale gas both here and
abroad, it is estimated that Ordos Basin is likely to become the
next basin to make a breakthrough in shale gas development in
China.
5. Similarities and differences in shale gas between China
and the US as well as revelation from exploitation thereof
Q3
Compared with the US, the shale gas in China is charac-
terized by various reservoirs, remarkable tectonism, difference
in thermal evolution degree, distinction in horizontal distri-
bution of reservoir, complex crustal stress condition, fluctua-
tion in surface condition and burial depth of marine shale in
Yangtze Region.
5.1. Comparison of shale gas between China and the US
There is difference in shale gas reservoir between China
and the US in terms of sedimentary structure, thermal evolu-
tion degree, sweet spot size, crustal stress feature and gas
component etc. (Fig. 5).
Including: (1) Shale reservoir in North America is based on
marine deposit, with stable structure. Shale in China shows
marine deposit, continental deposit and transition deposit, having
subjected to multi-stage tectonic transformation in reservoiring
process. (2) Shale reservoir in the US is moderate in maturity,
being in the preferred gas production stage, with Ro from 0.8% to
2.0%, marine shale in China is in high and over maturity stage,
with Ro value from 2.5% to 4%, continental Ro value from 0.8%
to 1.5%. (3)Sweet spot section in shale reservoir in North
America is thick (30e150 m). Sweet spot area reservoir is in
continuous distribution in large area (10000 km2); Sweet spot
section in shale reservoir in China is relatively thin (10e40 m),
big difference in distribution of reservoirs (from 100 km2 to
10000 km2). (4) Shale reservoir in North America is simple in
crustal stress, unobvious in horizontal main stress and likely to
