5.2. Revelation from exploitation of shale gas in the US
It is observed from shale gas development and case analysis
of typical gas field in the US that effective development of
shale gas resource necessitates innovative idea, innovative
technology and innovative management mode, with revelation
obtained including 4 points: (1) Shale gas reservoir is in
continuous distribution, in case that a breakthrough is made at
one point, the technology to make a breakthrough shall be
generalized in the whole area, therefore, it is possible to build
the shale gas reservoir into a big gas field in short period. (2)
Effective development of shale gas field is the result of con-
stant progress in geologic theory and engineering technology,
the breakthrough in multi-stage fracturing technology for
horizontal well achieved production revolution in develop-
ment of shale gas for the first time. (3)Multi-well pad
operation based on low oil and gas price greatly improved
operation efficiency and reduce cost and achieved self cost
revolution in beneficial development of shale gas for the
second time.(4) The tax deductions and exemptions and
project support by the US government in the shale gas
exploration and development in prior period have promoted
development of shale gas industry.
5.3. Challenge to development of shale gas in China
5.3.1. Non-marine shale gas potential to be further
confirmed
There is big difference in understanding of shale gas
resource in China among various departments. A breakthrough
has been made in development of marine shale in Wufeng
Formation-Longmaxi Formation in Sichuan Basin, the devel-
opment potential of transitional and continental shale gas is to
be confirmed. It is observed from evaluation by EIA (2015) in
the US that the shale gas in China is 31.6  1012 m3 in
recoverable resources, including 23.3  1012 m3 in marine
facies, 7.4  1012 m3 in transition facies and 0.9  1012 m3in
continental facies [51,52]. It is observed from evaluation by
Ministry of Land and Resource (2015) in the US that the shale
gas in China is 21.8  1012 m3 in recoverable resources,
including 13  1012 m3 in marine facies, 5.1  1012 m3 in
transition facies and 3.7  1012 m3 in continental facies
[52,53]. The evaluation by Research Institute of Petroleum
Exploration and Development (2014) shows that the shale gas
in China is 12.85  1012 m3 in recoverable resources,
including 8.8  1012 m3 in marine facies, 3.5  1012 m3 in
transition facies and 0.5  1012 m3in continental facies
[54e56]. The marine shale in south of China is characterized
by brittle mineral content no smaller than 60%, high brittle-
ness, convenience for fracturing and large reservoir space
(average porosity from 5% to 6.2%), having become the main
